The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Corporate Briefs

 Modi-Revlon, a joint venture between the Modi group and international cosmetics firm Revlon, will start its production unit for perfumes in India by June. We are looking at strengthening our position in the Indian fragrance market. Our unit at Modinagar in Uttar Pradesh will go onstream by June, said Amit Kumar Ghatak, senior manager, marketing, Modi-Revlon. He said the company would manufacture body sprays, eau de toilette, colognes and aftershave lotions at the new facility.

 Shyam Telecom expects to double its revenues to Rs 500 crore in 2008-09. The company is planning to set up a mobile manufacturing facility at Baddi in Himachal Pradesh in the next two years. It is also looking for acquisitions in Europe or Asia as part of its expansion plans and has earmarked $40-50 million for the purpose. 

 Redington India has posted a 37 per cent rise in profit after tax at Rs 101.7 crore for 2006-07. Revenue has increased 33 per cent at Rs 9,067.14 crore in 2006-07 compared with Rs 6,793.56 crore a year ago. The board of directors has recommended a dividend of 25 per cent.

 Glenmark Pharmaceuticals has received the USFDAs approval to market the pravastatin sodium tablets. 

 Airtel has introduced the lifetime prepaid at a lower price point of Rs 495 only. 

 Timond has launched gold and diamond studded watches for men. The series is priced at Rs 1,06,000. 

 Priya Yours, the fruit and beverage division of the Priya group, has launched its A-for-Apple product in 300 ml and 600ml packs. 

 S. Kumars Nationwide Ltds turnover for the quarter ended March 31, 2007 is Rs 1,229.54 crore and not Rs 1,2229.54 crore as published in the May 14 edition of the Business Telegraph.

